            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>This Week's Google Ads Account Suspension Observations</h2>
<p>According to monitoring by the Yiyu Digital Media operations team this week, multiple clients' Google Ads accounts received various types of suspension notices. Landing page violations accounted for approximately 45% of suspensions, payment-related issues for about 30%, with the remainder being policy violations and invalid traffic triggers.</p>
<p>Notably, Google strengthened its review of cross-border e-commerce and financial landing pages this week. Some accounts entered "restricted" status without warning—while ads were still running, the account was already suspended. This caught many operations staff off guard.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Common Causes of Account Suspension</h2>
<p>Before preparing appeal materials, identify the root cause of the suspension. Common reasons include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Landing page inaccessible or slow loading</strong>: Server unreachable in certain regions or page response time exceeding thresholds</li>
<li><strong>Page content doesn't match ad promises</strong>: Landing pages advertising low prices actually require subscription to view pricing</li>
<li><strong>Missing required legal statements</strong>: Privacy policy page missing or incomplete, especially for European and American markets</li>
<li><strong>Payment method rejected or insufficient balance</strong>: Credit card rejection, prepaid card risk controls, account arrears</li>
<li><strong>Suspicious traffic patterns</strong>: High click volume in short periods, overly single-source traffic, identified as invalid traffic</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>Appeal Materials Preparation Checklist</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Download Official Suspension Notice</h3>
<p>Log into Google Ads, navigate to "Account Settings → Compliance" and download the complete suspension reason. <strong>Don't judge the violation type solely by email subject lines</strong>—emails often give vague "policy violation" prompts, with real details only visible in the backend.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Collect Landing Page Materials</h3>
<ul>
<li>Complete URLs and screenshots of current landing pages</li>
<li>Page load speed test reports (recommend using PageSpeed Insights)</li>
<li>SSL certificate status screenshots</li>
<li>Privacy policy page URL and content screenshots</li>
<li>Refund policy, contact information, and other required elements</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Tip</strong>: If the landing page was recently updated, provide before-and-after comparison screenshots to demonstrate problem resolution.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Prepare Account Operation Records</h3>
<ul>
<li>Screenshots of the past 30 days of ad delivery history</li>
<li>Records of budget and bidding adjustments for affected campaigns</li>
<li>Screenshots of conversion tracking configuration</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 4: Draft Appeal Email</h3>
<p>Email structure recommendation:<br />
1. Account ID (10-digit format) and company name<br />
2. Clearly acknowledge receipt of the suspension notice<br />
3. Briefly describe completed corrective measures (don't write extensively)<br />
4. Commit to specific measures for future compliant operations<br />
5. Request re-review</p>
<p><strong>Tone Tips</strong>: Avoid emotional expressions, don't accuse Google of misreview, and don't over-explain background. Reviewers handle numerous cases daily—concise, professional statements are more likely to receive quick processing.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Three Recommendations for This Week's Suspensions</h2>
<p><strong>Recommendation 1: Don't Submit Repeated Appeals</strong></p>
<p>After account suspension, some operations staff submit continuous appeals, hoping to "increase visibility chances." In reality, repeated submissions get flagged as low priority, extending processing time. Wait 3-5 business days before submitting a second appeal.</p>
<p><strong>Recommendation 2: Prepare Backup Accounts in Advance</strong></p>
<p>For businesses with significant ad budgets, prepare backup Google Ads accounts in advance, binding different payment methods. When the main account has issues, the backup account can quickly take over traffic, reducing losses from business interruption.</p>
<p><strong>Recommendation 3: Prioritize Payment Issue Resolution</strong></p>
<p>If the suspension reason involves payment issues, resolve the payment method first, then submit the appeal. The review team typically verifies the account's payment capability first; without resolving payment issues, the appeal approval rate is extremely low.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Weekly Trend Summary</h2>
<p>Google Ads has recently tightened review standards for cross-border operations, especially for e-commerce and financial advertisers targeting European and American markets. This week, all overseas businesses should audit their account status, ensuring landing pages, payment methods, and privacy policies meet the latest requirements. If you encounter suspension, following the checklist above to prepare materials will significantly improve appeal approval rates.</p>
